I wanted to share more tips about how to get the most out of the
Find papers workflow. One of the features that distinguishes Elicit from other literature review tools is automatic data extraction. 

 

Once you ask a query and see some relevant papers, you can add columns to extract information across all of the papers. 

 

In a second, you can immediately see information like:

• Main findings

• Intervention

• Outcome measured

• Independent variables

 

 And so much more! 

 

If one of our 30+ predefined columns don’t fit your needs, ask a custom question! 

 

You can click on the cell to see supporting quotes from the paper. You can open up the paper to see the quotes in the context of the paper. 

 

If the paper is open access, we get information from the full text. Otherwise, we use information from the abstract. 

 

Here are some pointers on improving results from columns ( https://support.elicit.com/en/articles/878273 ) and creating custom columns ( https://support.elicit.com/en/articles/906049 ).
